## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2018 Allscripts ransomware attack** — a healthcare IT vendor whose systems were taken offline by ransomware, affecting thousands of physician practices and hospitals that depended on Allscripts for EHR and practice management services.

What made this case relevant to tailoring is the contingency planning dimension. Many of the affected practices had not developed downtime procedures specific to their clinical workflows — they had accepted the standard baseline contingency planning controls without supplementing them to reflect the operational reality that their entire clinical operation depended on a single vendor's platform.

When Allscripts went down, practices that had tested downtime procedures and had paper-based backup workflows were able to continue seeing patients with degraded but functional operations. Practices that had not were effectively unable to operate.

The standard NIST contingency planning baseline is designed for a generic enterprise system. A clinical EHR system — whether it is Allscripts, Epic, or OpenMRS — requires supplementary controls that account for the specific clinical operational context. The Allscripts incident is a clear example of what happens when the baseline is accepted without the supplementary tailoring that the actual risk environment requires.

